{"id":8924,"date":"2020-07-09T07:41:42","date_gmt":"2020-07-09T12:41:42","guid":{"rendered":"https:\/\/www.underconsideration.com\/brandnew\/archives\/new_logo_and_identity_for_british_geological_survey_by_threerooms.php"},"modified":"2020-07-09T07:41:42","modified_gmt":"2020-07-09T12:41:42","slug":"new_logo_and_identity_for_british_geological_survey_by_threerooms","status":"publish","type":"post","link":"https:\/\/www.underconsideration.com\/brandnew\/archives\/new_logo_and_identity_for_british_geological_survey_by_threerooms.php","title":{"rendered":"New Logo and Identity for British Geological Survey by Threerooms"},"content":{"rendered":"<p>(Est. 1835) &#8220;The <a href=\"https:\/\/www.bgs.ac.uk\/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">British Geological Survey<\/a> (BGS) is a world leading applied geoscience research centre that is part of UK Research and Innovation (UKRI) and affiliated to the Natural Environment Research Council (NERC). BGS core science provides objective and authoritative geoscientific data, information and knowledge to inform UK Government on the opportunities and challenges of the subsurface. It undertakes national and public good research to understand earth and environmental processes in the UK and globally. The BGS annual budget of approximately \u00a360 million pa is funded directly by UKRI, as well as research grants, government commissions and private sector contracts. Its 650 staff work across the UK with two main sites, the head office in Nottingham and Lyell Centre, a joint collaboration with Heriot Watt University in Edinburgh. BGS works with more than 150 private sector organisations, has close links to 40 universities and sponsors about 100 PhD students each year.&#8221;<\/p>\n<!--more--><figure class=\"full\">\n<img src=\"https:\/\/www.underconsideration.com\/brandnew\/archives\/british_geological_survey_logo.png\" alt=\"New Logo and Identity for British Geological Survey by Threerooms\" \/>\n<figcaption>Logo.<\/figc